ippsec — the method: workflow habits + signature moves
==========================================================================
The fourth altitude in this repo. The others answer "what command for this
service?" (hacktheplanet), "how do I turn a crash into a shell?" (exploitdev),
and "how do I get past the defender?" (evasion). This one answers the question
that sits ABOVE all of them: "what do I actually DO, in what order, and what do
I do when I'm stuck?" — the working method distilled from IppSec's HackTheBox
walkthrough catalog (youtube.com/c/ippsec) and the ippsec.rocks index.

It is deliberately NOT a command dump — per-service syntax lives in
~/hacktheplanet (`htp`). This file is the connective tissue: the recon loop, the
shell-stabilization discipline, the scripted pseudo-shell, and the unsticking
playbook that decide WHICH of those commands you reach for and WHEN.

It folds in vim/neovim exactly like the others: each section is wrapped in marker
banners and the modeline at the bottom wires foldmethod with no extra config —
open with `vim ippsec` (or `ipp`), toggle a fold with `za`, close all with `zM`,
open all with `zR`.

SCOPE FIRST. Everything here is the method for AUTHORIZED engagements (written
ROE + defined scope) and your own CTF / HTB lab boxes. The discipline that makes
this method professional — note-taking, an audit trail, re-enumeration — is the
same discipline that keeps you inside scope. Engagement DATA lives in
~/engagements (`mkengagement`), never in this repo.


The one motto — "always be running recon"
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# IppSec's single most-repeated lesson: enumeration is the whole game, and the
# "stuck" state is almost always solved by re-reading data you already have or
# scanning something you skipped — NOT by a cleverer exploit.
#
#   "The only thing you can't hack is time… if you don't have the discipline to
#    keep going back, running recon, you're going to get to the point where
#    you're just stuck."
#
# Operationalize it as three habits:
#   1. Recon is a BACKGROUND JOB, never a blocking step. Kick off the slow scans
#      (full-port, UDP, big wordlist bust) and START WORKING the fast results
#      while they run. Come back as each finishes and ask "what else can I run?"
#   2. RE-ENUMERATE after every new foothold. New user, new host, new network
#      position = run enumeration AGAIN from there. The next path is usually
#      already visible from where you just landed.
#   3. When a recon task finishes, take ONE minute to think up the next thing to
#      run before you move on. That pause is the method.
////////////////////////////////////////


When you're stuck — the unsticking playbook
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# Stuck almost never means "I need a 0-day." Walk this list before anything else.
# (The famous lesson box was Sneaky: stuck until he computed the link-local IPv6
#  address from a MAC and reached an SSH port he'd skipped. Scan what you skipped.)
#
#   [ ] Did you scan UDP?              nmap -sU --top-ports 100   (SNMP 161 leaks creds)
#   [ ] Did you scan ALL TCP ports?    nmap -p- --min-rate 10000  (not just top-1000)
#   [ ] Is there a second vhost?       fuzz the Host: header — the real app hides there
#   [ ] A localhost-only service?      ss -lntp on the box — pivot/forward to reach it
#   [ ] Re-read your OWN notes/output. The cred/hint is usually already captured.
#   [ ] Try every cred EVERYWHERE.     reuse across ssh/smb/winrm/web/db/su — relentlessly
#   [ ] Re-run enum AS THE NEW USER.   sudo -l, groups, readable files change per-user
#   [ ] Look at it from the box's POV. what can THIS host reach that you can't?
#   [ ] Search ippsec.rocks for the tech/keyword — find the video that shows it.
#   [ ] Walk away for 10 minutes. Genuinely. Then start at the top of this list.
////////////////////////////////////////


ippsec.rocks — the index is a tool, use it
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# ippsec.rocks indexes the spoken + on-screen text of every video. Search any
# keyword — "forward shell", "kerberoast", "SSTI", "log poisoning", a tool name,
# even an error message — to jump to the exact video and timestamp that
# demonstrates it. It is the single most useful companion to the channel.
#
# `rocks <keyword>` (offensive.zsh) opens the search for you. Treat "I don't know
# how to attack X" as a SEARCH, not a wall: someone has almost certainly filmed it.
#
# Pair it with note discipline: when a search teaches you a technique, write the
# command into ~/hacktheplanet (or your engagement notes) so next time it's muscle
# memory, not another search.
////////////////////////////////////////


Note-taking discipline — the unglamorous force-multiplier
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# The community consensus from IppSec's followers: "ALWAYS MAKE NOTES… it will
# really help you when you hit a wall." Re-reading notes IS the standard unsticking
# move (see the playbook above), and in a real engagement the notes ARE the report.
#
#   note "<text>"   append a timestamped line to the engagement's notes.md
#   logshell        record a full script(1) transcript for the audit trail
#   `mkengagement`  seeds notes.md + scope.txt; `cde` jumps back to the tree
#
# What to capture, every time, without exception:
#   - The moment of each state change: "got www-data via X", "cracked svc_sql".
#     IppSec's stated goal for parrot-build logging was exactly this — so you can
#     answer "when did I get the reverse shell?" from a log, not memory.
#   - Every credential the instant you find it (user:pass:source, NThash, key).
#   - Every host/port/vhost as you discover it.
#   - The command that worked — verbatim, with the real values — so the report's
#     Reproduction section writes itself and you can re-run it after a lost shell.
////////////////////////////////////////


The nmap rhythm — fast sweep, then scripted, then don't forget UDP
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# The standard cadence (full per-service syntax + rustscan/masscan in ~/hacktheplanet):
#   1. fast all-ports sweep:   nmap -p- --min-rate 10000 -oA scans/alltcp <ip>
#   2. scripted on found ports: nmap -p<list> -sCV -oA scans/scripts <ip>
#   3. UDP top-ports IN PARALLEL: nmap -sU --top-ports 100 -oA scans/udp <ip>
# Always -oA (saves .nmap/.gnmap/.xml — you'll want the grep-able + machine forms).
#
# Run the slow -p- in a SECOND terminal so it never blocks your -sCV work. IppSec's
# habit to keep them from stepping on each other: stagger the start a few minutes —
#   sleep 300 && nmap -p- --min-rate 10000 -oA scans/alltcp <ip>
# Then come back and feed the full-port results into a second scripted scan. This is
# "recon as a background job" made concrete.
////////////////////////////////////////


Catch a shell, then STABILIZE it — non-negotiable, first thing
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# The moment you catch a dumb shell, upgrade it to a full TTY. Losing a shell to an
# accidental Ctrl-C, or being unable to run su/ssh, wastes far more time than the
# 20 seconds the upgrade costs. (`ttyup` in offensive.zsh prints this with YOUR
# local rows/cols already filled in.)
#
#   # 1. on the TARGET — spawn a real pty:
#   python3 -c 'import pty;pty.spawn("/bin/bash")'      # or: script -qc /bin/bash /dev/null
#   # 2. background it:           Ctrl-Z
#   # 3. on YOUR box — hand the raw terminal to the remote, then foreground:
#   stty raw -echo; fg
#   # 4. press Enter once or twice, then on the TARGET:
#   export TERM=xterm           # makes clear / less / vim / curses work
#   stty rows <R> cols <C>      # match YOUR window — get <R>/<C> from `stty -a` locally
#
# Payoff: tab-completion, history, working Ctrl-C, and the ability to run su / ssh.
# If your local prompt is wrecked after the shell dies, run:  stty sane   (or: reset)
# (The stty raw -echo trick was Phineas Fisher's; IppSec popularized it in HTB.)
////////////////////////////////////////


Code execution ≠ a shell — script a pseudo-shell instead
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# A true IppSec signature: when a bug gives you blind/awkward RCE (SSTI, command
# injection, deserialization), DON'T fight for a reverse shell. Wrap the primitive
# in a Python cmd.Cmd loop so every line you type runs on the target and the
# response is regex'd back. Enumerating through this beats tampering one Burp
# Repeater request at a time, and it sidesteps egress firewalls entirely.
#
#   ~/.config/kali/templates/pseudo-shell.py  is a ready-to-fill starting point
#   (the templates dir is symlinked there by bootstrap.sh). Copy it INTO the
#   engagement's exploit/ dir, wire up the request + the capture regex, run it.
#
# The pattern (one method to edit — default() — and one regex to set):
#   from cmd import Cmd
#   import re, requests
#   class Term(Cmd):
#       prompt = "rce> "
#       grab = re.compile(r"START(.*?)END", re.DOTALL)   # bracket YOUR output to grep it out
#       def default(self, line):
#           r = requests.post("http://target/inject", data={"x": payload(line)})
#           m = self.grab.search(r.text); print(m.group(1).strip() if m else "[no output]")
#   Term().cmdloop()
#
# IppSec reuses this across Gobox/Backend/Validation/Ethereal. Once it's stable,
# THEN decide whether you even need a real reverse shell (often you don't).
////////////////////////////////////////


Forward shell — RCE behind ingress AND egress firewalls
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# When no reverse OR bind shell is possible (firewalled both ways) but you have
# blind RCE, IppSec's forward-shell technique (github.com/IppSec/forward-shell,
# with 0xdf) builds named pipes in /dev/shm and tails them into /bin/sh, then
# drives stdin/reads stdout over HTTP:
#
#   mkfifo /dev/shm/in; tail -f /dev/shm/in | /bin/sh 2>&1 > /dev/shm/out
#   # then loop: write a command to /dev/shm/in, read /dev/shm/out, over your RCE
#   # `upgrade` step runs:  python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash")'
#
# Best explained in his Sokar / Stratosphere videos — search "forward shell" on
# ippsec.rocks. The public repo intentionally leaves one piece as a DIY challenge.
# Reach for this only when the pseudo-shell above isn't enough because you need a
# stateful shell (cd, env, interactive tools) rather than one-shot command output.
////////////////////////////////////////


Read the exploit before you run it — and expect to edit it
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# IppSec's discipline with public PoCs: READ and MODIFY, never run blind. The
# header comment is often a lie about which build it targets, and a few PoCs carry
# a destructive payload or a troll. (searchsploit -x / -m workflow is in
# ~/hacktheplanet.) The things you almost always have to change:
#   - LHOST / LPORT / target IP / any hardcoded URL or path
#   - a stale CSRF token / VIEWSTATE / session cookie the PoC hardcoded
#   - offsets / return addresses for the EXACT target build (see ~/exploitdev)
#   - Python2 -> Python3 (print(), bytes vs str, urllib -> requests)
# For web CVEs he often just REWRITES the PoC cleanly with `requests` rather than
# trusting someone else's. Proxy your script through Burp (--proxy 127.0.0.1:8080)
# so you have the full request history to debug against.
////////////////////////////////////////


The phase loop in one screen — where each move lives
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# The IppSec method as a cycle. Every arrow back to recon is "always be running
# recon" in action. Concrete commands for each box are in ~/hacktheplanet (`htp`).
#
#   RECON ──► you have a service/version
#     │         searchsploit + a quick read; enumerate the app; fuzz vhosts/dirs
#     ▼
#   WEB / SERVICE EXPLOIT ──► you have code execution
#     │   SQLi · cmd injection (try the X-Forwarded-For header) · LFI+log poison
#     │   · SSTI {{7*7}} · XXE · deserialization · file-upload · SSRF · JWT forge
#     ▼
#   STABILIZE ──► full TTY (above) OR a scripted pseudo-shell (above)
#     │
#     ▼
#   LOCAL ENUM ──► privesc vector            ┌─ Linux:  sudo -l · SUID · caps · cron ·
#     │   linpeas/pspy, but VALIDATE manually │           PATH/python-lib hijack · GTFOBins
#     ▼                                       └─ Windows: SeImpersonate -> PrintSpoofer/
#   PRIVesc ──► root / SYSTEM / next user                 GodPotato · service ACLs · creds
#     │
#     ▼
#   RE-ENUMERATE AS THE NEW PRINCIPAL ──────► back to RECON  (this arrow is the method)
#     │   AD? graph it: BloodHound -> Kerberoast/AS-REP -> PtH -> DCSync -> ADCS (certipy)
#     │   Another subnet visible now? pivot: ligolo-ng / chisel / ssh -D, then nmap it.
#     ▼
#   COLLECT for the report: note "<what changed>", screenshot, save the working cmd.
////////////////////////////////////////


